The theme for this year's project is Data for Social Good. 
Our project provides a visualisation of agregated data from multiple sources to make relocation easier to and within Ireland. This is the JobMap team project report.


## User Scenario: The Characters

### The Target User

Employment and accommodation are among the top three barriers to migration into Ireland and also contribute to people emigrating from Ireland. The objective of our project is to provide an application that helps with job searchers in Ireland. A particular focus for our application is people looking to relocate into Ireland or within Ireland.

Search is a complex task, especially when it involves multiple different sources. Our goal is to simplify the retrieval and presentation of information to help our target user with their decision making.

In developing this project idea, we considered user scenarios to help identify the features and functionality for the solution. The scenarios outlined below will help illustrate our target users.

Pamela is a recent graduate who is searching for a job. She is open to moving out of Dublin. She does not drive. Some considerations as she searches for a job are:

- The historical trend for jobs in other counties. Mariam wants to know that a county she moves to has a sustained employment rate over recent years.
- Job listings
- Accommodation in close proximity of her job location as she does not drive

Chad is interested in moving to Ireland from US. He does not know much about job opportunities across Ireland nor does he know about job sites or accommodation sites. He is currently doing research for move. He is interested in an application that can help him identify suitable parts of Ireland where he can readily find a job and accommodation in his profession.

### Why They are Important

Employment is an important social issue. Employers need to attract and retain staff at a time of skills shortages. A survey by Hays found that 75% of employers had experienced some difficulty filling roles. The same survey found that 29% of employers expect to hire people from outside the country to fill roles.

Jobs and accommodation go hand in hand. Employees need somewhere to live. Several papers and surveys have highlighted the impact of jobs and housing on relocation in Ireland. A 2017 report by Indecon found that employment was the 3rd biggest barrier to returning emigrants after housing and motor related issues (Table 4.1 [https://www.dfa.ie/media/dfa-2017/globalirish/Report-on-Returning-Emigrants-2018.pdf](https://www.dfa.ie/media/dfa-2017/globalirish/Report-on-Returning-Emigrants-2018.pdf)). From the viewpoint of the employer, a research paper from the American Chamber of Commerce found that &quot;The availability of quality and affordable accommodation has a direct impact on the hiring of talent&quot;.

### The Problem We Address

Our solution is a web-based application to assist people in their search of jobs and accommodation. Our particular focus is providing this information to assist with relocation. By simplifying access to information on two of the major barriers to relocation, we believe our application helps address the problem. We achieve this by providing users with an interactive interface with the following features:

- The ability to identify the counties with a greater density of relevant jobs
- The ability to drill down and pinpoint the location of a job
- The ability to quickly locate accommodation within a selected radius of the job

## Technical Problem: The Setting

### Why JobMap Exists

Job hunting can be difficult and time consuming especially if accommodation is also needed. A lot of effort goes into getting information, analysing it and then making informed decisions, our application aims to simplify this process for users by aggregating data and presenting it in a visualized manner.

Previously, users would have had to visit multiple sites for jobs and accommodation, look up locations, correlate these on a map and then figure out distances; our application does that for them. The set of information that the web application provides includes:

- Job trends on a county level
- Indicating the number of jobs per county
- Accommodations in close proximity of jobs availability
- Map that shows the distance between place of work and nearest accommodation options.

### The Core Technical Problem

The core technical problems revolves aggregating data from multiple sources, integrating data from multiple sources and visualization.

**Aggregating data**

The manual process of searching for information on jobs and housing involves accessing multiple web sites and carrying out multiple searches independently. A user may search jobs.ie for information on jobs in their field. For each suitable job, they may then access [www.myhome.ie](http://www.myhome.ie) to carry out a search for accommodation.

JobMap aggregates the information into a single interface for the user. We still provide a link to the source sites to enable the user to apply (or to examine the listings in more detail). We however extract summary information to aid the user such as the job title, salary and company name.

A key technical challenge was the retrieval of data from disparate sources with different access methods (REST API for the CSO; SOAP API for jobs.ie and JavaScript Scraping for myhome.ie). Each source provided a different means of access and different formats for the data returned.

**Data Integration**

JobMap addresses the problem of locating jobs and housing on the same map. To do this, we needed to geocode address data and correlate proximities using longitude/latitude data.

The challenge we found here was that address data was not always reliable to facilitate geocoding. Some instances of this were:

- Missing address fields - jobs.ie allows jobs to be listed with no address information
- Duplicate location names across counties and countries (for example, Blackrock in Dublin and Cork; Dublin in Ireland and Ohio US).
- Missing company names

**Visualizations**

A critical part of the JobMap application is the presentation of information in visual format. data presented in visual format helps to reveal, &quot;information that is otherwise difficult to notice when presented in a textual environment&quot; (Hirsch et al. 2009).

Visualizing the data presented a number of technical challenges:

**Marker Density** - Some locations such as Dublin and cork had higher densities for Jobs and accommodation. In these locations, we needed to avoid presenting information in the format below and find a more meaningful representation.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

**Page refresh** - JobMap allows the user to drill down from a heatmap visualisation to an interactive Google map. This requires the application to be able to update the interactive map based on a user&#39;s selection in the heat map without refreshing the whole page.The user must also be able to reset the interactive map independently without refreshing the overall page. The wiring of the heatmap to the interactive map and refreshing components of the page independently also presented a tecchnical challenge.


### Competitor Products

From our research, there are existing applications that address various aspects of our solution but in isolation. There is no solution that provides the breadth of our solution. Some of the existing applications are described below.

**Glassdoor Jobs Explorer**

The closest competitor we came across is the Glassdoor Jobs Explorer. This tool appears to be very similar to our proposed application with the major difference being that it addresses jobs alone and not accommodation.

There is very little information available about this following its release in 2014 and it appears to be available for the US only.

Beyond this, existing solutions fall into the following categories :

**Jobs aggregators** - These simply pull in positions from multiple job sites. Examples are [www.indeed.ie](http://www.indeed.ie) and www.jobsmarket.ie.

**Jobsites with a map** - jobs sites showing job listings at a county level but without the drilldown to a more detailed map representation. An example from jobs.ie is shown in the below. Clicking on a county simply returns a search of all job listings for the county.

- **Property sites with maps** - Another category is  interactive maps (generally based on Google maps API) to show information about properties. This is quite common for accommodation sites. The map shows other properties nearby and allows a user to zoom in for more details of the area.

### What Sets JobMap apart

The key distinction of JobMap is that our functionality encompasses the functionality provided by our competitors.

JobMap acts as an aggregator by retrieving information from multiple sources that are of interest when relocating. We provide the heatmap feature of Glassdoor Job Explorer with the added ability for a user to drill down to an interactive map. We also provide an interactive map for accommodation listings. Finally, we provide an interactive map for job listings which does not currently exist on the market.



## Technical Solution: The Plot 

### What JobMap Does?

The jobmap web application simplifies the process of locating jobs and accommodation. It does this by providing the following:

- Aggregating data from different job and accommodation sites into a single interface
- Providing a heat map with enables users to quickly identify counties with a greater density of jobs
- Enabling drill-down from the heat map to a Google map to pinpoint job locations
- Enabling users to find accommodation in close proximity to a selected job
- Providing filters for users to limit accomodation searches by price range

### How it works?

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

#### Front-end technologies and user interface components

Our frontend is a web application that uses HTML, CSS and JavaScript. The CSS is used for designing the layout of the application. We used the Bulma CSS framework for the layout. The functionality is then provided by JavaScript embedded as source files.

We also use Google Maps JavaScript API, D3.js and Vue.js for the frontend. Google Maps is used to add an interactive map to the application. D3.js is used as the framework for other visualisations provided by the application, namely, a heatmap and graphs.

**Historical charts**

The historical charts present data on job trends in different counties. The data for the charts comes from Central Statistics Office data sources. The charts were created using D3.js.

**Heatmap**

One of the features of the application is a heatmap. The heatmap is used to visualize the density/concentration of jobs in different counties. The heatmap data comes from jobs.ie. The data presented is a count of the jobs in each county for a selected industry. The heatmap colour densities were graded using ranges for the job counts. This approach avoided the scenario where the higher job density locations (Cork and Dublin) severely overshadowed other counties.

The heat map was created using D3.js. This library was chosen as it is widely used for map visualisations but also because it gave the ability to click on the map for drill-down that other simpler tools could not provide.

For the heatmap, we first create a D3 path element and then bind a geojson data file of Ireland counties to the path. Later on we bind a json file containing job counts for each county onto the map for reflecting different colour depths.


 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

**Interactive Map**

The other key visualisation feature of the application is the use of an interactive map with markers. The interactive map is a drill down from the heat map. The map is displayed as the next level down when a user clicks on the heat map and it shows the location of jobs and accommodation from jobs.ie and myhome.ie respectively. The address data from these sites is geocoded into longitude and latitude from the Google geocoding API. This geocoding is then displayed as map markers using the Google Maps JavaScript API.

We evaluated a number of alternative applications that offer this functionality (such as Mapbox and Leaflet), before selecting the Google Maps JavaScript API. The API was selected for its extensive documentation and robust set of functions for markers. We also selected this API as it aligns closely to the Google geocoding API which could be used for converting addresses to coordinates via an API call.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

The application also requires the ability to load the interactive map independently of the other parts of the page. To enable this, we utilised the Vue.js JavaScript library.

#### Back-end technical components

**Apache Web Server**

The web server serves requests from application users. We have used the free, open-source Apache web server. Apache is the most widely used public-facing web server with 44.1% of public-facing sites running on this platform as at February 2017. Apache integrates into Django using the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI). This is done by deploying the mod\_wsgi module on the Apache server.

**Django Web Framework**

We are using the Django web application framework. Django uses Python which is one of the most popular programming languages and the language used for this project. Django was selected for its wide adoption, ready documentation and strong support for the model-view-controller (MVC) support.

**Database Server**

MySQL is our chosen database server. MySQL is a fast, reliable and open source Relational Database Management System. MySQL can also be easily managed using visual web tools such as phpMyAdmin. Django integrates with MySQL using the MySQL client.

#### Data resources

We access a number of external data sources to retrieve the data used by the application. The details are provided below.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

**Central Statistics Office (CSO)**

The data collected from the CSO is to show long term historical trends for industries, and overall job trends. The data is available from 2008 to 2016 and is intended to show the overall high-level trend for jobs in a county. This data is static and is retrieved as a once-off download for the trend graphs.

The CSO data is available via an API. The API presents the data in JSON-stat format. This is a JSON format designed for statistical data that using a cube model. We use the pyjstat python library for retrieving and manipulating the data. Pyjstat is the standard library for JSON-Stat data and enables the manipulation of JSON-stat data using data frame structures.

**Jobs.ie**

The data from jobs.ie is used to provide job counts in the heat map. This source is also queried for address data to locate addresses on the interactive map; as well as to extract other job information such as salary rates and employer details.

Jobs.ie provides a free API with a number of SOAP web services that can be queried to provide specific data. We use the Zeep library to access the jobs.ie SOAP API. Zeep is a SOAP client for python that is well suited for consuming web services. We opted to use Zeep as it is recent and well maintained.

**Myhome.ie**

Myhome.ie is a premier site for housing in Ireland. They do not provide an API for access, however, from carefully reviewing their terms and conditions, we confirmed that they allow data to be downloaded and used from their site so long as it is not for commercial enterprise.

We retrieve the data from myhome.ie using Scraping. The site uses JavaScript extensively. The use of JavaScript results in the data being masked as JavaScript elements (rather than as HTML source). We scraped the data from the site using Selenium for Python with the Chrome Web Driver. This facilitated the extraction of the data from JavaScript elements before passing to BeautifulSoup for manipulation.

After retrieving data from this site, we carry out some transformation. Essentially, this is to extract relevant features and then geocode the address of the property. The data is then stored to the database.

**Google Maps API (geocoding)**

We use the Google Maps Geocoding API to geocode addresses of job locations and properties. This allows us to retrieve the coordinates that can be used to place markers on an interactive map.

The Google Maps Geocoding API is a simple REST API that requires an API key. It can take an address as input and returns co-ordinates as JSON or CSV format. The example below illustrates an API call to retrieve information for EZ Living in Navan, who had an open position.

[https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?](https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=ez+living+navan&amp;key=AIzaSyCz6UpAb5gNS2MYUihPfKlrrUa_LnYdgB8)[**address=**](https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=ez+living+navan&amp;key=AIzaSyCz6UpAb5gNS2MYUihPfKlrrUa_LnYdgB8)[ez+living+navan&amp;](https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=ez+living+navan&amp;key=AIzaSyCz6UpAb5gNS2MYUihPfKlrrUa_LnYdgB8)[**key=**](https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=ez+living+navan&amp;key=AIzaSyCz6UpAb5gNS2MYUihPfKlrrUa_LnYdgB8)[AIzaSyCz6UpAb5gNS2MYUihPfKlrrUa\_LnYdgB8](https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=ez+living+navan&amp;key=AIzaSyCz6UpAb5gNS2MYUihPfKlrrUa_LnYdgB8)

For the JobMap application, we retrieve the data in JSON format. From the JSON, we are able to extract the longitude and latitude. We are also able to verify additional data souch as county.

**Data Retrieval Schedule**

Celery and Redis are used together for task scheduling. These are used to schedule the scripts to retrieve data from the external data sources. The data is then stored locally in MySQL after transformation. The periodic tasks we would be handling with celery are listed below. Each of these will run daily, with the geocoding running only after completion of the data retrieval from myhome.ie and jobs.ie.

Celery is a task queue and and a common tool for handling background tasks in a Python/Django environment. It is available as a simple pip install and integrates fully with Django.

Redis acts as a message Broker and stores tasks for distribution between Celery worker processes.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- **CSO** - The CSO data is essentially static. The data is released annually. We download the CSO data on a monthly schedule. This approach ensures that we will have the data updated no more than a month after it is released by the CSO.
- **Jobs.ie** - The jobs.ie data is retrieved daily. For each download, we download jobs data going back 30 days. This approach is taken as jobs.ie expire jobs after 30 days. We schedule the download to run at 1AM.
- **Myhome.ie** - The myhome.ie data is also retrieved daily. For this site, we simply download all available data at the download time. This download also runs at 1AM.
- **Google Geocoding API** - the API is used to geocode address information from jobs.ie and myhome.ie. To ensure that the address data is available, we run this task at 6AM to allow sufficient time for the address data to be downloaded.

### Data Challenges

**API Availability**

A major issue at the outset was getting access to APIs, in particular for property sites. We found that although a number of sites had APIs, they were not available for public access. In some cases, there were lengthy delays before the sites confirmed we would **NOT** be allowed an API key.

We also had concerns about the ethics of bypassing APIs and directly scraping data from sites. After reviewing the terms and conditions of a number of sites, we found that the myhome.ie site allows data to be downloaded for personal, non-commercial use.

**API Limits**

API limits present another challenge. The Google Geocoding API specifically has a monthly free credit of $200. This is equivalent to a limit of 40000 free geocoding requests. Beyond this, a charge applies.

Overall, we geocode approximately 1200 addresses daily. This falls into the free API credit, avoiding a charge from Google.

**SOAP API Performance**

A challenge we initially found with the jobs.ie SOAP service was speed. We found that we were only able to retrieve about 6 jobs per minute at the start of the script and this rate slowed further as the script ran. We had concerns that in addition to the slow performance of the script, we may also be impacting the performance of the remote application server.

After some investigation, we were able to increase this rate to over 150 per minute by downloading the web service wsdl file onto the local machine. This reduced the script time from hours to minutes.

**Agency Jobs**

We found that agency job advertisements skew the jobs data as the same job may be advertised by different agencies. At the outset of the project, the scale of this issue was unclear.

We tried a number of approaches to help identify the scale. The first step was to do a comparison of data returned from web service calls. First, we set a filter on the web service to exclude agency jobs. Then we ran the service again to include agency jobs. A comparison of the two sets of data was then done to identify the difference. What we found from this was that:

- Some agency jobs were not duplicates. They are only advertised by one agency.
- Some agencies do not mark their jobs in jobs.ie as agency roles. This may be to avoid being excluded by a filter.

The next approach we took was to attempt to use document similarity. As we did not have any classification of the documents done, we used Jaccard similarity to test. We did this by:

1. Tokenizing the job descriptions, preprocessing (stopwords, lemmatizing) and using a TF-IDF matrix
2. Use Jaccard similarity to identify similarity between documents. For each job, we identified the top 3 jobs in the same county with a similarity greater than 95%
3. Where jobs were similar, we manually examined them to check if they were duplicates

What we found from this exercise was that there were a high number of false positives. This was the case particularly for jobs with brief descriptions. We also found that the actual number of duplicates seemed low, consistently appearing to be well below 1% of the data set.

Based on the above, we have simply included the duplicates in the data set as it does not appear to skew results.

**Data Cleansing**

**Jobs expiry -** Jobs expire after 30 days by default. We pull data daily for the last 30 days only. This limits the occurrence of expired jobs in the data.

**Duplicate jobs data** - Jobs.ie allows the same job to be allocated to more than one industry and more than one county. The industry and county specified in the job listing are lists with the most appropriate as the first entry. To address the duplication, we check for duplicate job IDs and drop any duplicates. We then select only the first industry and first county in the job listing as the assigned industry and county.
